n prices is driven predominantly by the lower gas prices experienced during this period. \n• Total day-ahead make-whole payments were up from $22.4 million in spring 2023 to $24.0 million in 2024. Outside of January 2024, day-ahead make-whole payments were in the $5 million to $10 million dollar range for the last 15 months. \n• Total reliability unit commitment make-whole payments were down from $26.3 million in spring 2023 to $25.0 million in 2024. Gas resources, particularly simple-cycle resources, accounted for most of the decrease. Much of the decrease compared to spring 2023 can be attributed to a decrease in natural gas prices. \n• Total revenue neutrality uplift for spring 2024 was $59 million, down from $64 million in 2023. The change can be mostly attributed to higher levels of joint operating agreement adjustment charges (market-to-market) in spring 2024. \n• Average hourly load for the 2024 spring season was two percent above 2023, while the peak hourly load was flat compared to 2023. Average hourly load in April and May were both above the previous year’s levels, while March was slightly below the previous year. The hourly peak for April was up 10 percent from the previous year, while March and May were virtually unchanged from 2023. \n\n• Wind generation was the primary fuel type in terms of generation during the spring 2024 quarter, accounting for 47 percent of total generation, an increase from 45 percent in\n\nSouthwest Power Pool, Inc. Market highlights Market Monitoring Unit\n\n2023. Gas, simple-cycle generation climbed from nine percent of total generation in spring 2023 to 12 percent in 2024, while gas, combined-cycle generation was down from 15 percent in 2023 to 13 percent in 2024. The increase in gas, simple-cycle generation can primarily be attributed to lower natural gas prices in spring 2024, in comparison to the prior year. Coal generation decreased from 22 percent of total generation in spring 2023 to 19 percent in 2024.\n\n• At the end 